liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Hi there, if you're just joining us, here's what we know so far about the protests unfolding in France: 45,000 police will be deployed to tackle rioting around the country as it braces for a fourth day of violence Police have cleared protesters from the central Paris square France's interior minister has shut down buses and trams and says the coming hours will be 'decisive' President Emmanuel Macron blamed violent video games and called on parents to keep teens at home Here's some additional info you've been asking about: What happened to 17yo Nahel? Where have protests been taking place? Why is social media being blamed for fuelling riots? What do the rioters want?

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: France's Justice Minister Eric Dupond-Moretti says officials are "dealing with very young teenagers" at protests. "Whenever parents are able to exercise their parental authority, and they fail to do so, I want there to be criminal liability," he said.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Justice Minister: 'Very young teenagers' at protests

children.content: France's Justice Minister Eric Dupond-Moretti says officials are "dealing with very young teenagers" at protests.
"Whenever parents are able to exercise their parental authority, and they fail to do so, I want there to be criminal liability," he said.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The mother of 17-year-old Nahel has said in an interview she blames "the one who took my sons life" in her first TV interview since the teen's death. “He didn't have to kill my son, there were other ways to do it," she told French program C à vous. "Killing babies like that... How long will it last? How many more children will leave?" The police officer involved is in custody. His lawyer says he is "devastated" and wants the family's forgiveness.
